The following is a timeline of the history of the city of [[Guantánamo]], [[Cuba]]. {{Dynamic list}} {{TOC right}}
==19th century== {{History of Cuba}} * 1822 - Town established.{{sfn|Britannica|1910}} * 1856 - Ferrocarril de Guantánamo (railway) begins operating (approximate date).<ref name=zanetti1987>{{cite book|author1={{Interlanguage link multi|Oscar Zanetti|es}} |author2= Alejandro García |title=Sugar & Railroads: A Cuban History, 1837-1959|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dIgCag5WZI0C|year=1987|publisher=University of North Carolina Press|isbn=978-0-8078-4692-6 |others=Translated by F. Knight and M. Todd}}</ref> * 1899 ** ''La Voz del Pueblo'' newspaper begins publication.<ref name=Ayer1902>{{citation |publisher=N.W. Ayer & Son |location=Philadelphia |year=1902 |title= American Newspaper Annual |chapter=Cuba: Guantanamo |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ie1VAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA983 }}</ref> ** Population: 7,137 city; 28,063 district; 327,715 province.<ref>{{cite book |author=[[United States Department of War|War Department]] |title=Census of Cuba, 1899 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cs0tAAAAIAAJ |year=1900 |publisher=[[United States Government Publishing Office|Government Printing Office]] |location=Washington DC }}</ref>
==20th century==
* 1903 - U.S. military [[Guantanamo Bay Naval Base]] established near city.{{sfn|Staten|2005}} * 1907 - Population: 14,559 city; 43,300 municipality; 455,086 province.<ref>{{cite book|editor1= Victor H. Olmsted |editor2= [[Henry Gannett]] |title=Cuba: Population, History and Resources 1907 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=m2czAQAAIAAJ |year=1909|publisher=[[United States Bureau of the Census]] |location=Washington DC }}</ref> * 1919 ** Teatro Fausto built.<ref name=cinema>{{cite web |url= http://cinematreasures.org/theaters/cuba/guantanamo?status=all |title=Movie Theaters in Guantanamo, Cuba |work=CinemaTreasures.org |publisher= Cinema Treasures LLC |location=Los Angeles, USA |accessdate= September 28, 2016 }}</ref> ** Population: 68,883.<ref>{{cite book |title=[[Statesman's Year-Book]] |year=1921 |location=London |publisher= Macmillan and Co.|chapter= Cuba |chapterurl= http://hdl.handle.net/2027/njp.32101072368440?urlappend=%3Bseq=836 }}</ref> * 1955 - Local [[MR-26-7]] political group active.<ref name="Cushion2016">{{cite book|author=Stephen Cushion|title=A Hidden History of the Cuban Revolution: How the Working Class Shaped the Guerillas’ Victory|subscription=yes |year= 2016|publisher=[[Monthly Review Press]]|isbn=978-1-58367-583-0 |pages=107+ }}</ref> * 1957 - Teatro Luisa opens.<ref name=cinema /> * 1964 - Population: 122,400.<ref>{{cite book |url= https://unstats.un.org/unsd/demographic/products/dyb/1960_round.htm |title=Demographic Yearbook 1965 |year=1966 |publisher=[[Statistical Office of the United Nations]] |location=New York |chapter=Population of capital cities and cities of 100,000 and more inhabitants }}</ref> * 1998 - [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Guantánamo-Baracoa]] established.<ref name=katolsk>{{cite web |title=Chronology of Catholic Dioceses: Cuba |url= http://www.katolsk.no/organisasjon/verden/chronology/cuba |publisher=[[Roman Catholic Diocese of Oslo]] |location=Norway |accessdate= September 28, 2016 }}</ref> * 1999 - Population: 208,030 city; 512,300 province.<ref name=Europa2002>{{cite book|title=South America, Central America and the Caribbean 2002|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=o9ODxqsr-dIC|year=2001|publisher=[[Europa Publications]]|isbn=978-1-85743-121-6 |series=Regional Surveys of the World }}</ref>
==21st century==
* 2002 - U.S. military [[Guantanamo Bay detention camp]] established near city.<ref name=bbc-timeline>{{citation |work=BBC News |title=Cuba Profile: Timeline |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-19576144 |accessdate=September 28, 2016 }}</ref> * 2014 - Population: 217,978.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://unstats.un.org/unsd/demographic/products/dyb/dyb2014.htm |work=Demographic Yearbook 2014 |publisher=[[United Nations Statistics Division]] |title=Population of Capital Cities and Cities of 100,000 or More Inhabitants }}</ref>
