The following is a timeline of the [[Montevideo#History|history]] of the city of [[Montevideo]], [[Uruguay]].
{{Dynamic list}}
{{TOC right}}

==18th century==
{{History of Uruguay}}

* 1726 – Settlement established by [[Spanish Empire|Spaniard]] [[Bruno Mauricio de Zabala]].
* 1778 – [[Free port]] status acquired.{{sfn|Britannica|1910}}
* 1797 – 31 August: British ship ''[[Lady Shore (1794 ship)|Lady Shore]]'' arrives in harbour.

==19th century==
[[File:Catedralmontevideo.jpg|thumb|Montevideo Metropolitan Cathedral was conseceated in 1804]]

* 1804 – [[Montevideo Metropolitan Cathedral]] consecrated.{{sfn|Mulhall|1885}}
* 1807
** 3 February: City [[Battle of Montevideo (1807)|besieged by British forces]]; British take city.
** [[Global spread of the printing press|Printing press]] in operation.
** ''[[The Southern Star (Montevideo)|Southern Star]]'' newspaper in publication.<ref name=worldcat>{{cite web |url= http://www.worldcat.org/search?q=su%3AMontevideo+%28Uruguay%29+Newspapers.&qt=hot_subject |title=Montevideo (Uruguay) Newspapers |location= US |work=WorldCat |publisher=[[Online Computer Library Center]] |accessdate=14 July 2013}}</ref>
** September: British occupation ends.
* 1811 – [[Siege of Montevideo (1811)|Siege of Montevideo]] by forces of the [[United Provinces of the River Plate]].
* 1812
** [[Montevideo Cabildo]] built.
** [[Siege of Montevideo (1812-1814)]] begins.
* 1814 – Siege ends; Spanish loyalists surrender.
* 1817 – 20 January: city occupied by Luso-Brazilian forces.
* 1821 – City becomes part of [[Brazilian province]] [[Cisplatina]].
* 1823 – [[Siege of Montevideo (1823)]]
* 1825 – Hospital de Caridad founded.{{sfn|Mulhall|1885}}
* 1828
** City becomes capital of independent [[Oriental Republic of Uruguay]].{{sfn|Britannica|1910}}
** [[The British Cemetery Montevideo|British Cemetery]] established.
* 1829 – City wall dismantled.{{citation needed|date=July 2013}}
* 1830 – National museum founded.{{sfn|Britannica|1910}}
* 1833 – Public library founded.{{sfn|Britannica|1910}}
* 1843 – [[Great Siege of Montevideo]] begins.{{sfn|Britannica|1910}}
* 1847 – Anglican church built.{{sfn|Britannica|1910}}
* 1849 – [[University of the Republic (Uruguay)|University of the Republic]] founded.
* 1851 – [[Great Siege of Montevideo]] ends.
* 1856
** [[Solís Theatre]] built.{{sfn|Salgado|2003}}
** Salesas convent founded.{{sfn|Mulhall|1885}}
** Epidemic.{{sfn|Mulhall|1885}}
* 1857 – British hospital founded.{{sfn|Britannica|1910}}
* 1858 – Church of the Immaculate Conception built.{{sfn|Mulhall|1885}}
* 1862 – Hotel Oriental built.{{sfn|Mulhall|1885}}
* 1863 – Bolsa (exchange) built.{{sfn|Mulhall|1885}}
* 1866 – Post office built.{{sfn|Mulhall|1885}}
* 1868 – Mercado del Puerto built.
* 1871 – Teatro Cibils inaugurated.{{sfn|Salgado|2003}}
* 1874 – [[Estévez Palace]] built.
* 1876 – [[Punta Brava Lighthouse]] erected.
* 1879 – Population: 91,167.{{sfn|Stanford|1883}}
* 1880 – Nuevo Teatro San Felipe opens.{{sfn|Salgado|2003}}
* 1885 – [[Escuela Brasil (Montevideo)|Escuela Brasil]] (school) established.
* 1889 – Teatro Nuevo Politeama inaugurated.{{sfn|Salgado|2003}}
* 1895 – Teatro Stella d'Italia founded.{{sfn|Salgado|2003}}
* 1900 – [[Estadio Gran Parque Central]] opens.

==20th century==
[[File:Stad de centario uruguay1930 montevideo.jpg|thumb|The [[Estadio Centenario]] opened for the [[1930 FIFA World Cup]]]] 

* 1905 – Teatro Urquiza inaugurated.{{sfn|Peck|1916}}
* 1906 – Electric streetcar begins operating.{{sfn|Rosenthal|1995}}
* 1908
** Municipality of Montevideo created.
** Daniel Muñoz becomes [[Intendant of Montevideo]].
** Immigrants' Hotel opens.{{sfn|Peck|1916}}
* 1909 – Urbano hotel in business.{{sfn|Peck|1916}}
* 1910 – Teatro 18 de Julio opens.{{sfn|Salgado|2003}}
* 1911
** [[National Museum of Visual Arts (Uruguay)]] inaugurated.
** May: General strike.{{sfn|Rosenthal|1995b}}
* 1913 – [[Villa del Cerro]] and [[La Teja]] become part of city.
* 1925 – [[Palacio Legislativo (Uruguay)]] built.
* 1930
** [[Estadio Centenario]] opens.
** July: [[1930 FIFA World Cup]] held.<ref name="Dunmore2011">{{cite book|author=Tom Dunmore|title=Historical Dictionary of Soccer|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9j1wbp2t1usC|year= 2011|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-7188-5}}</ref>
** [[Juan Manuel Blanes Museum]] established.
* 1933 – [[International Conference of American States]] held; [[Montevideo Convention|Montevideo Convention on the Rights and Duties of States]] signed.
* 1935 – [[Joaquín Torres García|Asociación de Arte Constructivo]] founded.<ref name=MMA-sa11>{{cite web |url= http://www.metmuseum.org/toah/ht/?period=11&region=sa#/Key-Events |title= South America, 1900 A.D.–present: Key Events |work= Heilbrunn Timeline of Art History |publisher=[[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] |location=New York |accessdate=30 November 2014 }}</ref>
* 1941 – [[Palacio Municipal (Montevideo)]] built.
* 1945 – Cine Trocadero opens (approximate date).<ref name=CinemaTreasures>{{citation |url=http://cinematreasures.org/theaters/uruguay/montevideo?status=all |title= Movie Theaters in Montevideo, Uruguay |work=CinemaTreasures.org |publisher= Cinema Treasures LLC |location=Los Angeles |accessdate=14 July 2013 }}</ref>
* 1947 – [[Carrasco International Airport|Airport]] terminal inaugurated.{{citation needed|date=July 2013}}
* 1952 – [[Cinemateca Uruguaya]] (film archive) founded.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cinemateca.org.uy/institucional.html |title=Institucional |publisher=Cinemateca Uruguaya |language=Spanish |accessdate=14 July 2013}}</ref>
* 1953 – [[Museo Torres García]] opens.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.torresgarcia.org.uy/uc_47_1.html |title=Historia del Museo Torres García |location=Montevideo |publisher=Museo Torres García |accessdate=14 July 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140514030118/http://www.torresgarcia.org.uy/uc_47_1.html |archivedate=14 May 2014 |df= }}</ref>
* 1956 – [[Cilindro Municipal]] (arena) opens.
* 1958 – Museum and Municipal Archives inaugurated in the [[Montevideo Cabildo|Cabildo]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cabildo.montevideo.gub.uy/node/4 |title=Historia |language=Spanish |publisher= Museuo y Archivo Cabildo |location=Montevideo |accessdate=14 July 2013}}</ref>
* 1963 – Population: 1,154,465.<ref>{{cite book |url= https://unstats.un.org/unsd/demographic/products/dyb/1960_round.htm |title=Demographic Yearbook 1965 |year=1966 |publisher=[[Statistical Office of the United Nations]] |location=New York |chapter=Population of capital cities and cities of 100,000 and more inhabitants }}</ref>
* 1964 – [[Edificio Panamericano]] (residential building) constructed.
* 1973 – 27 June: [[1973 Uruguayan coup d'état]].
* 1975 – Population: 1,229,748.<ref>{{cite book |url= https://unstats.un.org/unsd/demographic/products/dyb/1970_round.htm |title=Demographic Yearbook 1975 |year=1976 |author=[[United Nations Department of Economic and Social Affairs]], Statistical Office |location=New York |chapter=Population of capital city and cities of 100,000 and more inhabitants |pages=253–279 }}</ref>
* 1983 – September: Labor demonstration.<ref>{{Citation |publisher = Praeger |isbn = 0275977455 |publication-place = Westport, Connecticut |title = A history of organized labor in Uruguay and Paraguay |author = Robert J. Alexander |publication-date = 2005 }}</ref>
* 1985 – [[Liberty Building (Montevideo)]] built.
* 1988 – May: [[Pope John Paul II]] [[List of pastoral visits of Pope John Paul II outside Italy|visits]] city.
* 1990
** Tabaré Vázquez elected mayor.{{sfn|Canel|2001}}
** City administration partially decentralized.
* 1991 – Population: 1,360,258.<ref>{{cite book |url= https://unstats.un.org/unsd/demographic/products/dyb/1990_round.htm |title=1995 Demographic Yearbook |year=1997 |author=United Nations Department for Economic and Social Information and Policy Analysis, Statistics Division |location=New York |chapter=Population of capital cities and cities of 100,000 and more inhabitants |pages=262–321 }}</ref>
* 1992 – Sarandi street pedestrianized.{{citation needed|date=July 2013}}
* 1995 – 23 July: [[1995 Copa América Final]] football tournament held.

==21st century==
[[File:Torre Ejecutiva (Montevideo).jpg|thumb|Executive Tower, Montevideo]]

* 2007 – [[Mercosur]] headquartered in city.<ref name=bbc-timeline>{{cite web |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-20043130 |title=Uruguay Profile: Timeline |work=BBC News |accessdate=13 July 2013}}</ref>
* 2008 – [[Executive Tower, Montevideo]] built.
* 2009 – [[Carrasco International Airport]] expands.
* 2010 – [[Ana Olivera]] becomes [[Intendant of Montevideo]].
* 2011 – Population: 1,319,108.
* 2016 – Population: 1,380,432.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://unstats.un.org/unsd/demographic-social/products/dyb/index.cshtml |work=Demographic Yearbook 2016 |year=2017 |publisher=[[United Nations Statistics Division]] |title= Population of capital cities and cities of 100,000 or more inhabitants }}</ref>

